{"title_page": "Brandon R\u00edos", "text_new": "{{short description|American boxer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2013}}\n{{Infobox boxer\n| name = Brandon R\u00edos\n| image = Brandon Rios.jpg\n| caption = R\u00edos in 2011\n| realname = Brandon Lee R\u00edos\n| nickname = Bam Bam\n| weight = {{plainlist|\n*[[Lightweight]]\n*[[Light welterweight]]\n*[[Welterweight]]\n}}\n| height = 5 ft 8 in\n| reach = 68 in\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1986|4|29}}\n| birth_place = [[Lubbock, Texas]], U.S.<ref>[https://bambamrios.com/biography/ \"Biography\"]. bambamrios.com. Retrieved June 22, 2018.</ref>\n| style = [[Orthodox stance|Orthodox]]\n| total = 41\n| wins = 35\n| KO = 26\n| losses = 5\n| draws = 1\n| no contests = \n}}\n\n'''Brandon Lee R\u00edos''' (born April 29, 1986) is an American [[professional boxer]]. He held the [[World Boxing Association|WBA]] [[lightweight]] title in 2011 and has challenged once for the [[World Boxing Organization|WBO]] [[welterweight]] title in 2015. Nicknamed \"Bam Bam\", R\u00edos is known for his aggressive [[pressure fighting]] style, formidable punching power, and exceptionally durable [[chin (combat sports)|chin]].\n\n==Amateur career==\nR\u00edos compiled a stellar amateur record of 230\u201335. In 2004 he became the [[United States national amateur boxing featherweight champions|U.S. National Amateur Featherweight champion]], and was also a United States Olympic alternate at 125&nbsp;lbs.<ref>{{cite journal | title = Brandon R\u00edos Biography | journal = Boxrec | date = October 4, 2008 | first = Fernando | last = Luevanos| id = | url = http://boxrec.com/media/index.php/Brandon_Rios | accessdate = July 2, 2010}}</ref> \"When I met [[Roberto Garc\u00eda Cortez|Roberto]] in the Olympic trials in Mississippi, that\u2019s when Roberto came and worked my corner, which it was a bad mistake,\" Rios said as Garc\u00eda laughed. \"I should have never done that because my dad was my amateur coach through my whole career. You get used to one person and then you come with another guy and he doesn\u2019t really know you? To me, it kind of messed me up. But then again, I\u2019m glad we met because we exchanged information and he brought me down here.\"<ref>{{cite journal | title = What Drives Brandon R\u00edos | journal = MaxBoxing | date = July 5, 2011 | first = Gabriel | last = Montoya| id = | url = http://www.maxboxing.com/news/max-boxing-news/what-drives-brandon-rios | accessdate = July 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\n[[File:Brandon Rios & Margarito.jpg|thumbnail|R\u00edos (right) with [[Antonio Margarito]], 2011]]\nHe is signed to [[Bob Arum]]'s company [[Top Rank]].<ref>{{cite journal | title = Brandon R\u00edos with Top Rank | journal = Top Rank | date = August 26, 2009 | first = Alessandro | last = Mulei | url = http://www.toprank.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPID=73995&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=23700&ATCLID=204911379&Q_SEASON=2010 | accessdate = July 2, 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110717075625/http://www.toprank.com/ViewArticle.dbml?SPID=73995&DB_LANG=C&DB_OEM_ID=23700&ATCLID=204911379&Q_SEASON=2010 | archive-date = July 17, 2011 | url-status = dead }}</ref> On October 17, 2009,<ref>[http://www.caller.com/news/2009/sep/23/ready-to-rumble/ Ready to rumble \u00bb Corpus Christi Caller-Times]. Caller.com. 2009-09-23.</ref> R\u00edos got a TKO victory in the 7th round over [[Manuel Perez (boxer)|Manuel Perez]].<ref>[http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=22906 Brandon Rios Stops Manuel Perez in Seven Rounds \u2013 Boxing News]. Boxingscene.com (2009-10-18). Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref>\n\nHe next fought in a [[World Boxing Association|WBA title eliminator]] against the undefeated contender [[Anthony Peterson]], on a [[Boxing After Dark|HBO Boxing After Dark]] card.<ref name=\"boxingscene1\">Reeno, Rick (2010-06-15) [http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=28544 Peterson vs Rios as Co-Feature To Gamboa-Salido on HBO \u2013 Boxing News]. Boxingscene.com. Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref> Rios dropped Peterson to the canvas with a left hand at the end of the fifth round.<ref>Iole, Kevin. (2010-09-12) [https://sports.yahoo.com/box/news;_ylt=AqLQhlEUw8crw5px9XcRNIeUxLYF?slug=ki-091110gamboawins Scintillating Rios overshadows Gamboa \u2013 Yahoo Sports]. Sports.yahoo.com. Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref> In the sixth round, a desperate Peterson landed several low blows on R\u00edos, losing two points in the process.<ref>Donovan, Jake (2010-09-12) [http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=30875 Yuriorkis Gamboa Unifies, Continues The Hunt For Juanma \u2013 Boxing News]. Boxingscene.com. Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref> In the seventh round, Peterson landed low blows once again, prompting the referee to stop the bout and award R\u00edos a disqualification victory.<ref>[https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iQ8EoIcWCQRuewfN7NO0SBLpwvxgD9I657IO1 ]{{dead link|date=November 2013}}</ref> Brandon was leading on all three scorecards before the stoppage.<ref name=\"boxingscene1\"/> His next fight was the first [[HBO]] PPV fight on the undercard of [[Manny Pacquiao vs. Antonio Margarito|Margarito vs. Pacquiao]]. Bob Arum stated that if Rios beat [[Omri Lowther]] at Cowboys Stadium, Brandon would get a shot to fight against [[World Boxing Council|WBC]] [[Lightweight]] Champion [[Humberto Soto]] next. Rios won by TKO in the fifth round.<ref>[http://www.maxboxing.com/news/max-boxing-news/bam-bam-comes-out-of-the-bullpen News \u2013 \"Bam Bam\" Comes Out of the Bullpen]. Max Boxing (2010-11-10). Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref>\n\n===WBA Lightweight Championship===\nOn February 26, 2011, Rios defeated [[World Boxing Association|WBA World]] [[Lightweight]] Champion, [[Venezuela]]n [[Miguel Acosta]] via a 10th-round TKO, becoming the new WBA regular Lightweight champion.<ref>[http://www.vcstar.com/news/2010/dec/20/oxnards-rios-will-fight-for-world-title/ Oxnard's Rios will fight for world title \u00bb Ventura County Star]. Vcstar.com. 2010-12-20.</ref>\n\n====R\u00edos vs. Antillon====\n{{Main|Brandon R\u00edos vs. Urbano Antill\u00f3n}}\nBrandon's first title defense saw him face [[Urbano Antill\u00f3n]], in a bout that was previously expected to take place once before in May 2010. Rios won the fight by TKO in the third round.\n\n===Light Welterweight===\n\n====R\u00edos vs. Alvarado I & II====\nRios faced [[Mike Alvarado]] at the Home Depot Center in [[Carson, California]] on October 13, 2012. Rios was behind on the scorecards until the 6th round where in he hurt Alvarado with a crushing right. Rios was able to stop Alvarado in the 7th as referee Pat Russell stopped the bout at 1:57 of the round.<ref>[http://www.boxingnews24.com/2012/10/rios-tko-7-alvarado/ Rios TKO 7 Alvarado]. Boxingnews24.com (2012-10-13). Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref> The fight was voted the 2012 Fight of the Year by the ''[[Sports Illustrated]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/mma-boxing/photos/1212/boxing-awards-2012/1/|title=Fight of the Year \u2013 Brandon Rios defeats Mike Alvarado \u2013 2012 Boxing Awards|date=December 26, 2012|publisher=[[SI.com]]|accessdate=January 3, 2013}}</ref>\n\nA much anticipated rematch was held on March 30, 2013, at the Mandalay Bay in Las Vegas, Nevada. Like the first fight, both came in with a lot of fireworks as they continued to go toe to toe, until Alvarado changed strategy and became a lot more evasive and hard to hit with fancy footwork. Alvarado defeated Rios by unanimous decision with scores of 115\u2013113, 115\u2013113 and 114\u2013113. Top Rank promoter Bob Arum dismissed another rematch and suggested to let the two boxers face other fighters first.<ref>[http://www.boxing.com/men_o_war_alvarado_decisions_rios.html Men o\u2019 War: Alvarado Decisions Rios]. Boxing.com (2013-03-30). Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref>\n\n===Welterweight===\n====Rios vs. Pacquiao====\n{{See also|Manny Pacquiao vs. Brandon R\u00edos}}\nRios and Pacquiao battled for the vacant WBO International Welterweight title on November 23, 2013, at Cotai Arena in [[Macau]]. Rios was guaranteed a purse of $3 million for this fight which is the highest of his boxing career. On August 5, R\u00edos and Pacquiao hit the road on a U.S. tour promoting the fight. Pacquiao won the 12-round match and the WBO International Welterweight title very easily.<ref>{{cite web|title=Manny Pacquiao V. Brandon Rios U.S. Promotional Tour Begins Today|url=http://www.sportsmedia101.com/boxing/2013/08/05/manny-pacquiao-v-brandon-rios-u-s-promotional-tour-begins-today/|access-date=August 5, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130808093659/http://www.sportsmedia101.com/boxing/2013/08/05/manny-pacquiao-v-brandon-rios-u-s-promotional-tour-begins-today/|archive-date=August 8, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/10028892/manny-pacquiao-beats-brandon-rios-unanimous-decision|title= Manny Pacquiao wins in return|date=24 November 2013|work=ESPN|accessdate=25 November 2013}}</ref> After the fight, R\u00edos tested positive for [[methylhexaneamine]].<ref>{{cite web|title= Brandon Rios failed postfight test cite web|url = http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/10134718/brandon-rios-failed-drug-test-fight-vs-manny-pacquiao |date=13 December 2013|work=ESPN|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n====R\u00edos vs. Alvarado III====\nFollowing a disqualification win over Argentine [[Diego Chaves (boxer)|Diego Chaves]], a third fight was announced against old rival, Mike Alvarado. On January 24, 2015, in Alvarado's home town of [[Denver]], [[Colorado]], Rios punished Alvarado for 3 rounds before the referee stopped the fight prior to the start of the fourth.<ref>http://espn.go.com/boxing/story/_/id/11970707/brandon-rios-mike-alvarado-iii-set-jan-24-denver</ref>\n\n====R\u00edos vs. Bradley====\nOn November 7, 2015, Rios battled [[Timothy Bradley]] for the WBO Welterweight title at the Thomas & Mack Center in [[Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]]. He was unsuccessful in doing so, losing every round of the fight in the process before referee Tony Weeks called an end to the bout at 2:48 of the ninth round, marking the first time R\u00edos had ever been stopped in his professional career.\n\nDuring the emotional post-fight interview, Rios announced his retirement, stating that although he loved the sport, his body was no longer acting the same and that both weight fluctuations and layoffs were affecting his performances. He has since gone on record to say that he would also like to spend more time with his family and close friends now as well.\n\n====Comeback====\nRios made a comeback to the ring against Aaron Herrera on June 11, 2017, with new trainer Ricky Funez, after splitting with longtime trainer Robert Garc\u00eda. Rios won by KO in the 7th round.\n\n==Personal life==\nBrandon married Victoria L\u00f3pez in August 2010 and has three children and two from a previous relationship.<ref>[http://www.secondsout.com/usa-boxing-news/usa-boxing-news/brandon-rios-celebrates-honeymoon-in-vegas SecondsOut Boxing News \u2013 USA Boxing News \u2013 Brandon Rios Celebrates Honeymoon in Vegas]. Secondsout.com (2010-09-11). Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref> R\u00edos gave the names Laila, Mia and Ava to his three daughters, after boxers [[Mia St. John]] and [[Laila Ali]]. His two sons are named Brandon Jr. and Marcus Antonio respectively, the latter of which is after [[Mexican people|Mexican]] World Champion [[Marco Antonio Barrera]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/box/news;_ylt=ApH2HJdtxWNK9CIKHMy4OU2UxLYF?slug=ap-rios-antillon |title=Archived copy |access-date=January 14, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111019094141/http://sports.yahoo.com/box/news |archive-date=October 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nR\u00edos's dad is Mexican. R\u00edos's mom is from Texas, and she is a Native American of the [[Alabama people|Alabama tribe]].<ref>In a video titled, \"''boxing star brandon rios proud to be half native american - EsNews Boxing''\", which was published to YouTube on August 14, 2013, R\u00edos talked about being part Native American when R\u00edos said, \"''I am. Uh, the tribe that my mother is, is uh, Alabama. They're the [[Alabama people|Alabama tribe]], so that's, that's what I am. So, I'm half Alabama.''\" This quote starts at the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=s6of6t-RioE&t=1m24s 1:24 mark of the video], and the quote ends at the 1:32 mark of the video.</ref><ref>In a video titled, \"''brandon rios on being native american EsNews Boxing''\", which was published to YouTube on April 14, 2014, R\u00edos said, \"''I'm Native, half Native American, half Mexican. My, my dad's a [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]]. My mom's from Texas. Well they lived, she really grew up in a Native, fuckin' ranch whatever, Native ranch whatever.''\" A woman in the video then said, \"''Native, or the reservation''\", and R\u00edos responded, \"''Yeah, reservation...''\". The woman then asked, \"''Are you so, do you know anything about being Native American, like your culture?''\"  R\u00edos responded, \"''A little, not too much. Uh, I know we're uh, an Ala-, not Al-[[Apache]], fuckin' what were we are?''\". A man who was off camera answered, \"''You're the [[Alabama people|Alabama tribe]]. I looked it up''\". R\u00edos then said, \"''Alabama, Alabama tribe''\". The first quote by R\u00edos starts at the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zXxtR8-NMV8&t=0m10s 0:10 mark of the video], and the last quote by R\u00edos ends at the 0:38 mark of the video.</ref> R\u00edos said that the eagle tattoo on his chest is to represent both his Mexican and Native American ancestry.<ref>In a video titled, \"''Brandon Rios Half Mexican Half Indian Full Warrior''\", which was published to YouTube on October 14, 2011, R\u00edos talked about his tattoos when R\u00edos said, \"''I have uh, an Indian face, a portrait of an Indian and an eagle on the front of my chest.''\" A man who was off camera asked R\u00edos, \"''Why, why an eagle across your chest?''\" R\u00edos responded, \"''Because, it states for, I'm half, I'm half Indian, half Mexican, so it represents both.''\" The first quote by R\u00edos starts at the [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qfRYUxqw7YE&t=0m22s 0:21 mark of the video], and the second quote by R\u00edos ends at the 0:36 mark of the video.</ref>\n\n===Victor Ortiz feud===\nAs amateur boxers both R\u00edos and [[Victor Ort\u00edz]] fought out of the same boxing gym in [[Garden City, Kansas]], at the Garden City Boxing Club where they were both trained by Manuel R\u00edos.<ref>[http://bleacherreport.com/articles/495961-brandon-rios-wants-victor-ortiz Brandon Rios Wants Victor Ortiz]. Bleacher Report (2010-10-20). Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref><ref>Kim, Steve (September 14, 2010) [http://www.doghouseboxing.com/DHB/Kim091410.htm Boxing Flurries on Zab Judah, Brandon Rios, Yuriorkis Gamboa, Matt Remillard and More]. Doghouseboxing.com. Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref> For a short time Brandon's father trained Ort\u00edz when they both still lived in Kansas. Ort\u00edz would later move to Oxnard to train under Robert Garc\u00eda, R\u00edos also left Kansas after being invited by Garc\u00eda to train in Oxnard.<ref>Seckbach, Elie (October 5, 2010){{cite web|url=http://boxing.fanhouse.com/2010/10/05/brandon-rios-on-his-beef-with-victor-ortiz |title=Brandon Rios on His Beef With Victor Ortiz |accessdate=2010-12-13 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110117195140/http://boxing.fanhouse.com/2010/10/05/brandon-rios-on-his-beef-with-victor-ortiz |archivedate=January 17, 2011 |df=mdy }} . boxing.fanhouse.com</ref> In 2009 after an incident involving Brandon, Victor and Victor's younger brother Temo, their relationship became strained.<ref>Gabin, Ernest (2010-12-17) [http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=33917 Robert Garcia Sets the Record Straight on Victor Ortiz \u2013 Boxing News]. Boxingscene.com. Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref> A fight between R\u00edos and Ort\u00edz has been proposed at a catch weight of 138&nbsp;lbs or even at 140&nbsp;lbs, with R\u00edos stating on numerous occasions that he's gotten the better of Ort\u00edz many times during sparring when they were growing up.<ref>[http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=31517 Brandon Rios: Victor Ortiz is a Motherf**king Crybaby! \u2013 Boxing News]. Boxingscene.com (2010-10-04). Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref>\n\n===Freddie Roach incident===\nIn the much anticipated lead up to the Margarito vs. Pacquiao fight at Cowboys Stadium, R\u00edos made headlines along with [[Antonio Margarito]] and Robert Garc\u00eda when [[Elie Seckbach]] interviewed the three of them and showed the group mocking Manny Pacquiao's trainer [[Freddie Roach (boxing)|Freddie Roach]], who has [[Parkinson's disease]]. Elie Seckbach made a video response defending Rios and Margarito, and stated that the media misunderstood their gestures. Seckbach stated that they were actually making fun of Freddie Roach's comments where he (Roach) stated that Margarito was going to get knocked out. Garc\u00eda explained that R\u00edos was \"joking around\", and that Brandon was also unaware that Roach suffers from Parkinson's disease.<ref>Satterfield, Lem (2010-11-10) [http://www.boxingscene.com/?m=show&id=32704 Roach Wanted To Fight Over Video: 'I Hate Margarito, Rios' \u2013 Boxing News]. Boxingscene.com. Retrieved on 2013-11-25.</ref> In the video, R\u00edos himself explains that their gestures were a response to Roach's trash talking.\n\n==Professional boxing record==\n{{BoxingRecordSummary\n|draws=1\n|nc=\n|ko-wins=26\n|ko-losses=2\n|dec-wins=7\n|dec-losses=3\n|dq-wins=2\n|dq-losses=\n}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!{{abbr|No.|Number}}\n!Result\n!Record\n!Opponent\n!Type\n!Round, time\n!Date\n!Location\n!Notes\n|-\n|41\n|{{no2}}Loss\n|35\u20135\u20131\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|{{flagicon|MEX}} [[Humberto Soto